multi-domain OCR is to identify the text in images, it is used in many areas, such as image searching, document recognition, visual understanding and so on.

\begin{itemize}
\item single-domain OCR is to identify a specific type of text, such as documents, newspaper images, medical documents, handwritten notes and so on.
\item single-domain OCR is effective and efficient when working on a single type of text. However, when a single type of text is in different fields, such as different news or handwritten texts, it is hard to learn the features of these texts.
\item multi-domain OCR is capable of identifying different types of text, such as paragraphs, articles, resumes and so on.
\item It is an integrated approach to solving the problem. It can be used to solve problems in many areas. It can use the training data of these areas.
\item It is relatively inefficient, and the efficiency of multi-domain OCR in the single-domain OCR is about 20\%.
\item single-domain OCR only needs a small amount of data, but multi-domain OCR needs more data.

By the time the final Keyhole satellites were launched in 2000, the program had cost a total of $11.6 billion (adjusted for inflation, this is equivalent to $18 billion in 2009 dollars). 
The first Keyhole satellites were similar to the early optical systems used for surveillance during the Cold War and the Vietnam War, but the later Keyhole satellites were equipped with the advanced electro-optical systems. In their later stages, the satellites were able to provide images to the warfighters that were two to three times more detailed than those of the KH-11 or KH-7 satellites, allowing soldiers on the ground to recognize friends and enemies.

Answer: I have seen that to be true on multiple occasions. For example, I started programming in high school. I was well versed in multiple languages and cared a lot about the quality of code. The summer before my freshman year, I got a job at a small company that did Java development for a trading platform. They hired me specifically for my ability to quickly ramp up and learn things quickly. As a result, my work came in quickly, my code was solid and bug free. The feedback I received was outstanding.

I then went to school at a large public school and experienced a very different environment. Professors were not as concerned with students learning than delivering lectures, many of which students would just glaze over. The mentality was to get your degree and graduate and then apply. There was little or no mention of the technical skills that would help you land a job and to get ahead in the field.

I found that for my first job out of college I had to be much more proactive in looking for jobs and in my own career development. As a result, I have done freelance work on the side and kept myself sharp by learning new things in my free time. My code is always solid and well thought out.

Answer: I see the question as the difference between your own experience and that of other job applicants.  In general it's easier to get a job if you have a track record of doing a job - something that demonstrates your skill level.  If you have a track record of experience, you're less likely to find yourself up against a stiff competition.  If you don't, you're likely to find yourself up against more competition - but that doesn't make it necessarily any harder to get a job.  And, if you're hiring a junior developer, you're likely to be looking for someone who has the potential to develop a track record of experience.

Of course, you can never guarantee that you'll get a job because you have a track record - or that you won't get a job even if you don't.  In an ideal world, you'd be hired because of your skills - but an ideal world isn't always where we find ourselves.

(b) Any person who knowingly exposes his person or the private parts thereof in any public place, or in any place where there are present other persons to be offended or annoyed thereby, and who is a first offender, is guilty of a misdemeanor and shall be fined not more than five hundred dollars ($500.00).

(c) Any person who knowingly exposes his person or the private parts thereof in any public place, or in any place where there are present other persons to be offended or annoyed thereby, and who is a second or subsequent offender is guilty of a misdemeanor and shall be fined not more than seven hundred fifty dollars ($750.00).

(d) If a person is convicted of a second or subsequent offense under this section, the sentencing judge may impose an additional fine not to exceed five hundred dollars ($500.00) for each offense.

(e) A violation of this section may be punished concurrently with any other offense for which the violator may be charged.

(f) For the purposes of this section, the term "person" means the actor, or the actor's agent or employee, or the actor's principal by or through whom the actor is employed or who has the right to control the actor's conduct.

Public nudity in the state of Wyoming is illegal, except where specific exemptions are provided under state law. For example, there is an exception for sunbathing in the state park. Where other exemptions do not apply, it is generally illegal to be naked in public, unless in an appropriate place and time for legal nudism.

For example, under Wyoming statute § 6-2-306(a)(ii), it is illegal for "a person to appear in a public place in a state of nudity, or to expose a covered body part or to be otherwise naked in a public place...except in a place or manner wherein nudity is allowed by Wyoming statutes, an ordinance, resolution or regulation."

Wyoming statute § 6-2-307 further provides that "Nudity is allowed in the following areas and places: ...(g) ... to the extent allowed by the provisions of [Wyoming] statute 6-2-306."  It thus allows for public nudity in the following specified areas: 

* Places of exercise or amusement specified in the statute
* Certain approved private areas not specified in the statute

The state park provision may therefore be a legal method of public nudity in Wyoming. However, the provision requires that you may not expose "a covered body part."  Many parks in the state of Wyoming require that you wear clothing on the beach.

That question and its response ended up in my personal notes on chess playing computer programs and made me wonder whether there were similar sites in which one could pose simple questions and get answers from other players.

So, in late 2005 I decided to start the site and my quest to answer basic questions from other chess players.

def ask_sbd_split():
    """
    Ask the user for a sbd training split and return it
    """
    raw_input()

    split_str = raw_input("The split should be an integer from 100 to 0 (or hmm) ")

    if not split_str:
        split = 0
    else:
        split = int(split_str)
    return split


def return_sbd_split(sbd_split):
    """
    Convert the input to a percentage
    """
    return sbd_split / 100.0

A Brief Note About Extracting Information:

This is the simplest technique for obtaining informaion from any list of options. Typically, if the query is too complicated or unusual, you will not get the same results as your sample case. The program first tries to match the closest options in the sample list. If it does not, the next best matches are used. In both cases, however, the result is a "best" guess of what the user wants. This is a perfectly acceptable result in most cases, especially when you do not know what the user is trying to accomplish. For the situations where you do know exactly what the user wants, there are other ways to answer the question.

Creating an Incremental Form

The software allows you to ask the user questions in a sequence rather than in one shot. The sample example is for a single list, but it works just the same for multi-page lists. The method we use is that once a page is displayed, you first ask the user which questions (specific pages) should be displayed. The program creates a check box list of those options on a second screen. You can then send the user to that screen.

Incremental Forms are more difficult to create than Extracting Information, but they will almost always lead to a better result, especially when the user does not know how to use the software.

Incremental forms allow you to set a question in one page and have the user answer the question in a subsequent page (or page(s)). Here's an example:

## Overview

Cognitive computing is an emerging discipline that seeks to mimic the way the human brain works to process complex patterns, make connections, and recognize and respond to different types of information in the world. Since the brain works by drawing on prior knowledge, reasoning and understanding, and having access to context and other factors, it makes sense that computational modeling and analysis will also take into account what we know about what we are working on in order to suggest actions and ideas. The Human Connectome Project, for instance, uses cognitive computing to model how the brain's billions of neurons are connected and how they change as we think and perform different cognitive tasks.

We are likely to see cognitive computing in the near future to help us with specific tasks and needs in business and daily life. An intelligent assistant, for instance, can be programmed to analyze historical data to suggest stock market positions. It can also take into account additional context (information from third-party providers) to come up with stock recommendations that take into account tax implications and other criteria. At home, we may someday be able to ask our computers and tablets to find a "look-alike" to purchase that would match the look and feel of what we have now or to find a nearby hotel, restaurant, or even the best airfare for a trip we are planning.

The real-world applications of cognitive computing will be vast and are already being developed and used in practical ways. In business, IBM is investing in cognitive computing. Watson, its main "brand," helps medical doctors and healthcare organizations work with patients to come up with treatment options and other aspects of care. You had a long-standing lunch date in SoHo that suddenly felt pressing.  You hadn't given it much thought before.  Would he even be there?   You walked by his apartment.  You think you saw him.  But you don't know what it was.   Do you?

Meanwhile the doppelgänger keeps appearing.   Or is it a doppelgänger?   The delicious possibility of an interesting adventure draws you like a magnet.   You fantasize a meeting where you outwit the other you, making some kind of bold and decisive choice to determine your fate.   But wait—you might end up in a 30 second elevator ride with a stranger!   Would it be smart to make contact, or could this ultimately be something you don't really want?  The uncertainty of the choice (which has the power to help or harm) makes it almost better not to decide.   And so the game continues.

At what point does the game shift from a tolerable annoyance to a source of constant dread?  At what point does the thing-that-shall-not-be-named cease to be a concept and become a force in your daily life, a discomforting presence looming in the corner of your eye? class string_to_ints(Converter):
    name = "string_to_ints"
    description = """
    Convert string in integer form.
    Format: [int], [int, int], [int, int, int], [int, int, int, int], ...
    """
    def convert(self, str):
        str = [str]
        l = []
        while 1:
            l, sep, t = next(str)
            if not l:
                break
            if t == ']':
                res = l
                break
            res.append(int(t))
            t = sep
            if not l:
                break
        return res

Aye. The "th" sound is pronounced like "th",  "th",  "th"...  It is pronounced by pressing the tip of the tongue up against the roof of the mouth and allowing air to escape through the teeth.

When you do the opposite (pressing the tip of the tongue against the bottom of the mouth, and air to pass through the throat) you'll get the sound  "s".  Try it!

For example:
"three" -- say the number "three" a few times.  Now say the letter "t", just to familiarize yourself with how the sound of the letter "t" should feel.  Now repeat the "three" and press the tip of your tongue against the roof of your mouth and allow air to escape through your teeth and say the "th".  "Breathe" -- repeat the word "breathe".  Now try saying the word "breathe" again, and place the tip of your tongue against the bottom of your mouth.  Air will pass through the throat and you will hear the sound of "s".

Say the word "thin", making the "th" sound.

Now say the word "thick", making the "s" sound.

Say the word "hundred"

And then say the word "score".  Listen for the difference between the "th" and "s" sounds.  Which sound did you hear?

Once you can pronounce the sounds  "th" and  "s" on their own, try blending them together, so as to create the word "this" by using the "th" sound.  Now try saying the word "this" by using the "s" sound instead.

The easiest scenario to illustrate trust is:

User: Do you have a minute?

User: I’ve just moved to a new city where I don’t know anyone. I was wondering if you had some ideas on how to meet new people?

OpenAssistant has been under development since early 2016, based on the OpenCog framework for open artificial general intelligence (AGI). The current work builds on the OpenCog model by adding a feedback loop (based on neural networks), better and more flexible dialog systems, and the ability to provide useful results without re-training.

## Publicly documented

### General

Open Assistant has released an overall architecture diagram and a more detailed map to guide the understanding of how the system works. This and other documentation is updated frequently, so the best place to learn the details of the project is the documentation site: https://www.openassistant.org/docs.

### Opening a task

The human user of Open Assistant opens a task by saying, for example, "Hi, help me ..." In reality, however, it is in some sense possible to open any task: the simplest approach is to say, "Help me" and let the user interface open a "start help" task. This may lead the user to asking, "Well, how do I start help?" — at which point it is helpful to have a task for that. OpenAssistant can, when it needs, also automatically search the database for suitable help tasks for a question it thinks it has heard, based on a data-driven model of what kinds of information are likely to be needed in response to different questions. OpenAssistant also has a built-in help task that gets triggered automatically when it is a while since the last activity, which gives hints about using the system.

Answer: My answer is similar to Robert Columbia's.

I suspect the real reason is not so much that you are getting older and are forgetting things more readily. It is more likely that you have accumulated an enormous amount of knowledge during your life, so the things that you know are all competing with one another for space in your brain. As you get older, you continue to accumulate knowledge and there is less and less space left.

I suspect that your problem is more one of retrieving a particular memory from your vast memory storehouse than it is one of forgetting things. And as you get older, retrieval time gets slower and slower, and when you cannot retrieve the correct name of something, your brain remembers that you know the name and it is even more difficult to retrieve it because your brain believes that it is even more obscure than it really is.

Answer: Your assistant is making a common error.  The names of objects we know well are not "already in our heads."  Rather, we store the object's shape and/or behavior in our memory.  When we look at the object, we access that memory and then use that information to remember the name.

We are not born with a set of all possible names for objects.  We learn them through our interactions with the world.  So when we look at an object, we need to store the shape and behavior of the object in our memory.  When we look at a similar object, we already have that information in memory, so it is easy to remember its name.

Comment: +1 and a little more info for the OP. It is not just our brain cells that are being used, but our _connections_ between brain cells that are being used. As we get older, our neurons and synapses get fewer and weaker, so it takes more energy to remember things.

Answer: I would say that the most promising development in renewable energy is using the most common and widely used energy source: water.

The most obvious way of doing this is using solar power to evaporate water, then collecting that water to be used for energy. This is similar to how plants work, and it is extremely efficient.

The second method is to use solar panels to boil water, then use the steam to turn a turbine. The water then condenses and returns to the panels to be boiled again. This is called a solar still and is a very efficient method.

The third way is to use the power of the ocean. Ocean thermal energy conversion is a very promising method of harnessing the power of the ocean. It uses the temperature difference between the surface and the depths of the ocean to produce electricity.

All three of these methods of using water as a renewable energy source are extremely promising, and have been used to some extent in the past. The main drawback to these methods is that they can only be used when the sun is shining and the ocean is not too rough.

"Superstition" is "an irrational belief that purports to explain, or influence, events or phenomena." For example, a person who believes that the wearing of a red shirt will cause him to lose at cards, is believed to have a superstition. The belief that "break a mirror" will cause seven years of bad luck is actually a superstition. However, the term "superstition" is used for both a true belief and a false belief. Therefore, it is possible to find two people debating whether the "break a mirror" belief is true or false. They can both be right. One can be "true" from a scientific perspective and one can be "true" from a superstitious perspective. Therefore, the term "superstition" has no inherent meaning of "falsehood". 

As an example of a belief that is true in a scientific sense and also in a superstitious sense, consider lightning striking the same location more than once. Scientifically speaking, lightning does not "remember" a location. However, from a superstitious perspective, a lightning strike can "remember" a location and cause damage to something a second time, which causes seven years of bad luck. 

While the "seven years of bad luck" belief is a superstition, the principle of three strikes, not being able to predict the next person to break a mirror, or belief that mirrors should not be broken is actually a superstition.

### Modified speech model

Speech models are complicated things that take care of a lot of things about speaking language, such as proper sentence structure, stress, pronunciation, and pausing. When you speak to a bot, the system relies on a model of speech that is trained by humans and uses an algorithm to speak in a manner similar to how people talk.

The core idea behind this approach is that the person making the sentence uses their own voice, which is why it sounds much more realistic. The ideal output of the model would be a speech to text conversion system, a method used to convert words written on paper to words spoken. This output would be called the “Text-To-Speech” model, or TTS. If a bot’s model is less than perfect, it can be trained to use the TTS model.

In the training phase, bots can ask users a number of specific questions about their speech and what they want to say. Bots can also monitor conversations to help build up their own vocabulary and style. However, the model remains imperfect, so bots also use TTS systems to help build their own language.

The best control scheme for an industrial fan is a PID controller.

This is because the PID controller is a feedback control system that makes corrections to the input to the system in order to maintain the output of the system within a certain range.

The PID controller is a feedback control system. A feedback control system is a system that has a feedback loop. A feedback loop is a path of a signal from an output to an input. 
The PID controller uses a PID algorithm to calculate the correction to be applied to the output. This algorithm takes into account the error between the output and the desired output.

In the case of the PID controller, the PID algorithm is a linear equation. This means that the error in the output is directly proportional to the error in the input. In other words, the output will change by a certain amount every time the input changes by a certain amount.

The PID algorithm is a linear equation because it is a first order system. This means that the PID algorithm is a linear function. 
In the case of a first order system, the output will change in direct proportion to the input.

For example, if the input of the system is a function of time and the output of the system is a function of the input, then the PID algorithm can be expressed as the following equation.

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
y(t) = K_P (x(t) - x_d) + K_I (y(t) - y_d) + K_D (y(t) - y_d)
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

The x in the equation is the input and the y is the output. The K_P, K_I and K_D are the parameters in the PID algorithm.

Timsort is an in-place algorithm, meaning that it works on the input data directly and does not allocate any additional space.

By bias, the researcher means a synaptic weight that is often used to impose an overall bias to a neural network (like a strong minus sign to make the network favor negative inputs). Typically, a neural network is going to be trained to try to learn how to give high values to positive examples and low values to negative examples. It can't be trained without using a bias term. However, the neural network could still work well without using bias, just not as well. When the bias term is omitted, the net will have an overall trend to give slightly lower values to positive inputs and slightly higher values to negative inputs (which is actually similar to how you would want the net to work). However, without the bias term the net is not explicitly instructed to do that. This means that the net would be very sensitive to the precise setting of the bias term (which is not desired). Without the bias term the network could do worse or it could do better than instructed (which is not desired).

The bias value can be interpreted as the mean value of the output values.

If the data are structured and you have a priori knowledge of how the mean and variance will behave, then your bias term can be derived from the priori knowledge.

M=M_0+H*K

The units of the Hash rate and the number of cryptocoins is 1/s. The units of the market cap is USD.

M_0=1000

1000+500*100=1500

So the total market cap is 1500.

So, the market cap is equal to the hash rate times the current price of a coin times the number of coins in circulation.

I think the Assistant is an argument for a microscopic theory of pancake toasting.  Because the pancakes are heating at the speed of light at the top surface, and with no medium to travel through, the temperature gradient will fall off to zero.  So, if the pancake is not moving, a temperature gradient does not need to propagate through it in order to be measured.  The molecules get more unstable and interact more strongly, which may affect the speed at which the pancake toasts (for one batch or two), and their stickiness when done.

\strong{UPDATE:} I thought about this a little more, and one more very unlikely possibility: If the pancakes are contacting each other, then perhaps some crazy quantum effects are in play when they start to toast, and that may help the second batch of pancakes toast faster, since the particles are moving faster, and perhaps not all to a complete stop as in classical mechanics.  Then, the time to toast could be a function of the amplitude and phase of the quantum wave function, rather than the time taken to get to an equilibrium temperature in classical mechanics.

Dear Sir,

Thank you for your interest in our software.

For each file (2D/3D) with a specific extension (png, jpeg, ...) we are able to do a detailed calculation of the distribution of the optical density (molecular concentration) across the image.

Please notice that the optical density is not an image (it is the molecule concentration) but we use it for the visualization.

The software is able to recognize the brightness of the different pixel values.

For the 2D files we are able to calculate the optical density for each pixel.

The algorithm of the calculation is based on the intensity of the pixel and the variation of the intensity with the distance of the pixel.

The calculation is not linear but uses a curve fitting technique.

For the 3D files we are able to calculate the optical density for each voxel (3D pixel).

The software uses the distance of each voxel to the center of the image.

We can calculate the optical density for each voxel but we prefer to calculate it for the pixels (voxels) in the middle of the image.

We are able to calculate the optical density for each pixel (voxel) in the image.

The calculation uses a curve fitting technique and is not linear.

The optical density is a number between 0 and 1.

For example, the optical density for each pixel (voxel) is 0.5 or 0.7 for the two different files.

If you are interested in this calculation I can send you a demo.

The calculation has been done for several thousands of files and the software has been tested on different images.

The calculation is done in a very short time.

The software is provided as a service.

Answer: You could compare our organization to a thesaurus (not that I ever was a huge fan of thesauri!). The `~pastp` command specifies if a child have been provided for the `~cytosis` and `~plasmocytes` levels for an individual within `CHILD7/KIDINDUH`. So if you wanted to see for example if there is a relation between the age of a child and the number of cells in it's red blood cell count, you can use the following calculation:

`~pastp and ~cytosis and ~plasmocytes and age(child)`

If you wanted to see if the number of red blood cells is correlated with the birth-cohort (i.e. if the cohort has the lower number of red blood cells, then they are younger), you could do the following:

`~pastp and ~cytosis and ~plasmocytes and year(birth)`

As a final step, if you wanted to compare all children within CHILD7/KIDINDUH and see if a certain person had a more elevated red blood cell count, you could do:

`~pastp and ~cytosis and ~plasmocytes and country and ~birth (or yes/no).`

We use a NIR spectroscopy system with a 640 nm excitation source, and a 750-1100 nm emission wavelength range. For each chemical compound, the spectra is compared to a reference library of compounds (e.g., the NIST library) and the amount of each chemical compound is determined.

Assistant:
Here we use a method called "Chemometrics". In the process of chemometrics, the spectra are converted into a multidimensional "spectral space" with respect to the number of wavelengths. The spectral space is usually two dimensional, but sometimes it can be more. In our case, we use a 2-dimensional spectral space.

In the spectral space, the chemical compounds are represented by a "point", while the reference library of compounds is represented by a "vector". When we have a sample of unknown chemical compounds, we transform the sample's spectral space into the same spectral space as the reference library, then we calculate the "distance" between the "point" and the "vector". The smaller the distance is, the more similar the two compounds are. If the distance is very small, then we have very confident that the sample is the same as the reference.

Assistant:
The "distance" can be calculated by the Euclidean distance or other distance measures. In our case, we use the Euclidean distance to calculate the distance.

Assistant:
The Euclidean distance is the sum of the differences between the wavelengths of the two chemical compounds.

Assumption is a universal by-product of uncertainty.

In computer science, we make assumptions that may or may not be true.
In business, we make assumptions that may or may not be profitable.
In general life, we make assumptions that may or may not be fulfilling.

All this comes from uncertainty.  We make assumptions, not necessarily because we are uninformed, but because we're unsure.

We make assumptions not out of ignorance, but out of humility.

Before doing things programmatically in C++, let's take a moment to see how we'd do them in our normal lives.

Suppose I'm trying to write you a note.

There are several steps to writing such a note, all of which can be done in C++:

First, write:

```C++
    string text;
```

This is basically how we might initialize a variable in C++.

You can also rewrite "text" as "string text;" which is less readable but shorter. C++ is programmatically case-insensitive, so either is fine.

Second, make a sentence out of your note!

```C++
    text = "This is the best program ever!"
```

You see, we've gone a step further than what C++ normally does, and we've changed the text variable directly. This is called a direct modification.

Of course, a better way to make a sentence would be to use the "text" variable's string interface, by including some punctuation into the string and combining that with "This" and "is" and "the best" and whatever else you like. Here, we're using an indirect modification.

```C++
    text += "This is the best program ever!"
```

Or, you could have written:

```C++
    std::string::value_type* p = text.data;
    for (int i = 0; i < text.size(); i++)
        p[i] += "This is the best program ever!";
```

A language is a way of communicating with computers. 

The three words you’re asking about are terms that describe how a program is created, or how the computer “understands” the program that is created. 

A static language is one that is checked to make sure it is “correct” before it is executed. 

If the language isn’t “correct”, then the computer won’t run it. 

A dynamic language is one that isn’t checked before execution. 

If the language isn’t “correct”, then the computer will run it, and then it will do whatever it does (sometimes crash, sometimes not, depending on the language). 

A compiled language is one that is checked before execution. 

If the language isn’t “correct”, then the computer won’t run it. 

An interpreted language is one that is not checked before execution. 

If the language isn’t “correct”, then the computer will run it, and then it will do whatever it does (sometimes crash, sometimes not, depending on the language).

Statically typed, dynamically typed, and compiled versus interpreted is all about the structure of code.

Still other languages like Javascript and python are compiled from human readable code to something the machine can execute.

Programming languages usually fall into one of two groups: 

● Interpreted languages

● Compiled languages

● Interpreted languages are executed with minimal setup.

Programs are translated into machine code and executed directly by the machine. This has the advantage of being able to write and run a program immediately.

● Compiled languages run more efficiently because the compiler writes machine code that is optimized for your computer. This code runs faster and uses less memory.

To write programs using a compiled language, the programmer first writes a text file that contains the program in a special programming language. The compiler uses this information to create executable programs.

Once a compiler produces executable programs, it is important to remember that the program is now locked into the format of the language. That means the programs can’t be changed or debugged easily.

Because of this, programmers tend to prefer interpreted languages. This means there’s no need to convert the code into an executable file. You can make changes to the code whenever you want, and the compiled program can run almost instantly.

Compiled and interpreted languages both have their advantages, but a mixed bag.

But back to your question, compiled language uses a special computer program, the compiler, to transform a language into code, called an executable.

In an interpreted language, the interpreter takes the source code and converts it into a format it can use. Then the interpreter creates a runtime environment that is much smaller than an executable file and runs inside it.

Interpreted languages don’t use code compilers.

You don’t have to compile and convert the code to use it.

class Tailor(user_question):
    """
    Sums up a Question model, given its question text, without changing the question text.
    """
    def __init__(self):
        super(Tailor, self).__init__()

    def get_tailored_question(self, user):
        # We need to get the user's email from the Question model
        question = Question.objects.get(user=user)
        email = question.user.email
        return 'Do you have ' + question.question_text + '?'


    def tailor(self, message):
        """
        Sum up the answer to a question without changing the question's text.

        """
        text = message.subject
        tailored_text = 'A ' + text.capitalize() + ' got a ' + text
        text = text.replace(' ', '')
        text = text.lower()
        text = text.replace('.', '')
        text = text.replace('', '')
        return tailored_text

Quantum gravity is an area of investigation in physics concerned with the unification of general relativity, the theory of the large-scale structure of the universe, with quantum mechanics, the theory of the nature of matter and energy on the scale of atoms and elementary particles. The early history of quantum gravity is characterised by competing approaches based on different accounts of how quantum theory and gravity fit together. But the evidence for the failure of these approaches and the increasing realisation that a viable theory of quantum gravity is necessary if we are to understand quantum theory in its fullest sense has led to a consensus that quantum gravity theory is an important frontier of physics.

The various approaches to quantum gravity that exist today can be understood as attempts to reproduce the canonical formulations of quantum field theory in which the configuration variables take values in a Hilbert space that is generated by the space of all causal states and the Fock representation is obtained from the canonical GNS construction.

Thus, the core concepts of quantum theory are applicable to quantum gravity. We shall begin by reviewing the relevant aspects of quantum mechanics and quantum field theory that provide the main references to classical physics. We then summarise the importance of the canonical formulation of quantum field theory, including the foundation of the renormalization programme for physical theories via a Hilbert space representation of C*-algebras. Following this introduction, we will review how a free quantum field theory was developed and, even before full understanding of the novel properties of quantum field theory was achieved, attempts to formulate non-free fields gave rise to the Poincaré covariant formulations and some early attempts at quantum gravity. These developments culminated in a formulation in which the classical physics of general relativity is obtained as a limiting case. Answer: The ultimate fate of quantum gravity is the subject of some of the most heated debates in contemporary theoretical physics. There are two general approaches: that quantum gravity is consistent with a ‘large number of identical copies’ or ‘many worlds’ picture, and that it gives rise to unique classical states.

Supporters of the many worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics argue that there are some fundamental differences between the quantum description of a system and the description of its classical description. In other words, at some point a quantum system makes the transition to a classical one and maintains that description for all time. According to the many worlds interpretation, this transition occurs when the quantum system has reached a state that has an infinite number of microstates, in other words, when the wavefunction has evolved to its classical limit (also known as the decoherence limit). Such systems include those that arise in the study of quantum gravity.

A research team led by Professor Don Page at the University of Alberta in Canada have simulated what a quantum gravity system looks like at such a limit. The researchers created their quantum computer by storing data as a superposition of quantum states. In this form, it can be manipulated by computer algorithms in a controlled way, without damaging the delicate state of the system. The researchers then allowed the quantum computer to evolve until it had reached the state that is classically indistinguishable from a purely classical system.

In this state the computer had evolved to look like a classical system, with the information stored in the computer’s memory being in an indefinite state. This state is one of indeterminacy – the computer has a finite number of microstates and therefore the system would need to be measured to learn which microstate it was in.

Czech author Lukáš Navrátil, according to the journalist František Trávníček, wanted to come up with a successful follow-up to his very first novel Reizgání [Experiment] (1997), which had won a number of awards. The ideas originated from his work as a computer programmer in 1999, where he created a computer game, which was never finished. The first plot outline was written in 2000. He was inspired by writers such as Richard Matheson, H.P. Lovecraft, Iain Banks, John Wyndham, and H.G. Wells. The final novel was a rework of the previous three major storylines, each of which were about 200 pages long. The novel was originally supposed to be published in 2002, but the author thought it was too soon, and decided to give it a year to complete. After the death of his father in 2002, the novel had to be postponed to 2005. The book is named after the second most important and the most popular town in Moravia, where Navrátil was raised, named Olomouc (or Olomouce). The original rough draft was 500 pages, but it was shortened to 330 pages by the editor.

Comment: @GuyCoder sure I was just looking for a joke.

1. Start with the disables. You can disable signs and villagers from getting you stuff. Useful for weapons, potions, enchantments and banners. If you really need wood or coal, disable the villagers but only the ones who sell it.
2. Run to where the stuff is and go up and down the stairs and cut them if they don't have walls. Other than those two, cut the edge of the house and some corals. Use stone against zombie pigmen and skip building when skipping the hardest parts of the game. Be aware of the teleports.
3. When it comes to bosses, try to distract them with fireballs or skeletons before running away. Skeletons can also survive if you put a crafting table in their area. Push pigmen away with pistons and lower pressure plates to slow down the bullets.
4. Antlions fly over your head when you're building or lifting stuff. They will swarm over a minecart so that you can't have the opportunity to build on them. The only thing you can do is to get out of the minecart and run away.
5. If the smelter's on fire and can't be cooled down by piston, turn it off and turn on the iron armor beforehand. Stick around and use ghost lightning when it comes up the other way.
6. If you manage to beat the hardest part of the game, build a stair going down. Then burn all monsters up the stair, step on the lower side and open and build the trap. That way, you don't have to open the trap once there are monsters on the stairs.

Comment: Just to clarify: what you are asking about is not a proof of the fine structure constant, but how it relates to the speed of light.

Comment: Related: http://physics.stackexchange.com/q/34576/2451

Answer: You are asking how the fine structure constant relates to the speed of light.

The fine structure constant is a measure of how the electric charge behaves at very high energy levels, when the effects of QED can no longer be neglected. In particular, it is a measure of how a photon (a particle of light) interacts with the electromagnetic field.

So the fine structure constant is really a measure of how the electromagnetic field behaves at very high energy levels, when QED effects can no longer be neglected.

The speed of light is a measure of how a wave behaves, so it is a measure of how a photon behaves.

Now, the way that the fine structure constant relates to the speed of light is through the [fine structure constant equation](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fine-structure_constant#Fine-structure_constant_equation), which relates the fine structure

This constant describes the ratio between the strengths of the electric force
and magnetic force in a vacuum, 
and a related relationship between the speed of light and the strengths of these
two forces.

The reason it relates to the speed of light is that the maximum speed
of light in a vacuum (in a perfectly ideal vacuum, not our real vacuum)
is the speed of light, so it is the constant that is related to that
speed.

The reason for that: 
the fine structure constant can be written as an expression 
for a dimensionless number, which is the square of a dimensionless quantity. 
Because the speed of light is dimensionless, then this expression can be
multiplied by the speed of light and have a dimension, which is length.

Saying the maximum speed of light is the speed of light has something
to do with the fine structure constant, but you cannot say the fine structure
constant gives the maximum speed of light, since we do not know the maximum
speed of light. 
You cannot say that because this constant is how we calculate the maximum
speed of light. 
It has something to do with that number, but I'm not sure how the speed of
light is related to this number in the first place.

Also, the fine structure constant is one of the only untampered numbers 
in our quantum system.  This number is as we know it is.  There are some
speculation, and some ideas that the fine structure constant may vary 
somewhat, but that is not how we view the universe as it is, which is a
constant value.

Answer: Mentoring is about helping people develop. It's not about telling people what to do.  In fact, the better you are at mentoring, the less you will be telling people what to do.  The less you will be telling them, the more they will learn from you and become better.

This is why a great mentor listens first.  A great mentor listens to learn and to understand, and to develop a better understanding of their mentee.  This will help them tailor their advice better.

A great mentor encourages.  A great mentor will not tell people what to do, but they will encourage them.  A great mentor will build people up and help them grow.

A great mentor learns about the person they are mentoring.  A great mentor will not ask the same questions to everyone.  A great mentor will take the time to learn about the person they are mentoring, and develop their own understanding of that person.  A great mentor will learn about what they are good at, what they are passionate about, what they like to do, what they are interested in, and what they want

Great mentors are actually coaches. They understand their colleagues both on a personal and professional level. They also understand when to let go of their colleagues to help them develop. When you are in the role of a mentor, you are helping your colleague, while always placing yourself in their shoes to assess the situation better. It may be considered a simple act of listening, but sometimes that is all that your colleague may need to hear. Great mentors also understand the qualities, skills and expertise that their colleagues are looking to develop. They will ask questions to assess the interest of their colleague in this area, and set objectives for specific development areas such as public speaking or negotiation. They also place strong emphasis on their own expertise, and will point their colleagues to the best sources to hone their skills. Great mentors use all the tools at their disposal, including their communication skills and network of contacts to connect their colleague with the right source of knowledge and information to expand their skill sets. It is also about providing encouragement and motivation, knowing when to intervene with your colleague to turn things around and knowing when to step back and let them develop on their own. Mentors can be made, and their traits can be honed with proper training and some time in the role. All things in professional development require time and practice to get better at them.
